  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Introduction&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Decision tables are a precise yet compact way to model complex rule sets and their corresponding actions.&amp;nbsp;Like&#xD;
    flowcharts and if-then-else and switch-case statements, they associate conditions with actions to perform, but in many&#xD;
    cases do so in a more elegant way.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Decisions appropriate for inclusion in a decision table, and for use within an IT architecture,&amp;nbsp;are always&#xD;
    operational business decisions â€“ not programming, personal, strategic, or governance decisions. They very much control&#xD;
    operations and activities within the system. Decision tables provide answers to operational questions.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Structure&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Each decision corresponds to a variable, relation or predicate whose possible values are listed among the condition&#xD;
    alternatives. Each action is a procedure or operation to perform, and the entries specify whether (or in what order)&#xD;
    the action is to be performed for the set of condition alternatives to which the entry corresponds. Many decision&#xD;
    tables include in their condition alternatives the &lt;em>don't care&lt;/em> symbol, a hyphen. Using &lt;em>don't cares&lt;/em> can&#xD;
    simplify decision tables, especially when a given condition has little influence on the actions to be performed. In&#xD;
    some cases, entire conditions thought to be important initially are found to be irrelevant when none of the conditions&#xD;
    influence which actions are performed.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
